Face Mask Prediction using U-Net¶

Task is to predict the mask around the face in a given image.

Dataset¶

Faces in images marked with bounding boxes. Have around 409 images with around 1000 faces manually tagged via bounding box.

  • Data file name: images.npy

Note:¶

Here we can observe that the given images are with different sizes. One more thing we can observe is the channels count for some images is 3 and for some images is 4. We need to do the preprocessing to scale these images into same height, width and channels before fit into the model.

Set image dimensions¶

  • Initialize image height, image width with value: 224
In [47]:
IMAGE_HEIGHT = 224
IMAGE_WIDTH = 224

Create features and labels¶

  • Here feature is the image
  • The label is the mask
  • Images will be stored in "X" array
  • Masks will be stored in "masks" array
In [48]:
import cv2
from tensorflow.keras.applications.mobilenet import preprocess_input

masks = np.zeros((int(data.shape[0]), IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH))
X = np.zeros((int(data.shape[0]), IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH, 3))
for index in range(data.shape[0]):
    img = data[index][0]
    img = cv2.resize(img, dsize=(IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH), interpolation=cv2.INTER_CUBIC)
    try:
      img = img[:, :, :3]
    except:
      continue
    X[index] = preprocess_input(np.array(img, dtype=np.float32))
    for i in data[index][1]:
        x1 = int(i["points"][0]['x'] * IMAGE_WIDTH)
        x2 = int(i["points"][1]['x'] * IMAGE_WIDTH)
        y1 = int(i["points"][0]['y'] * IMAGE_HEIGHT)
        y2 = int(i["points"][1]['y'] * IMAGE_HEIGHT)
        masks[index][y1:y2, x1:x2] = 1

Create the model¶

  • Add MobileNet as model with below parameter values
    • input_shape: IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH, 3
    • include_top: False
    • alpha: 1.0
    • weights: "imagenet"
  • Add UNET architecture layers
In [58]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications.mobilenet import MobileNet
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Reshape, UpSampling2D, Concatenate, Conv2D
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model

def create_model(trainable=True):
    model = MobileNet(input_shape=(IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH, 3), include_top=False, alpha=1.0, weights="imagenet")

    for layer in model.layers:
        layer.trainable = trainable

    block2 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_1_relu").output ### Output shape of (112, 112, 32)   
    block3 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_3_relu").output ### Output shape of (56, 56, 128)
    block4 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_5_relu").output ### Output shape of (28, 28, 256)
    block5 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_11_relu").output ### Output shape of (14, 14, 512)
    block6 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_13_relu").output ### Output shape of (7, 7, 1024)

    x = Concatenate()([UpSampling2D()(block6), block5]) ### U-NET layer upsampling from (7, 7, 1024) to (14, 14, 1536)
    x = Concatenate()([UpSampling2D()(x), block4]) ### U-NET layer upsampling from (14, 14, 1536) to (28, 28, 1792)
    x = Concatenate()([UpSampling2D()(x), block3]) ### U-NET layer upsampling from (28, 28, 1792) to (56, 56, 1920)
    x = Concatenate()([UpSampling2D()(x), block2]) ### U-NET layer upsampling from (56, 56, 1920) to (112, 112, 198)
    x = UpSampling2D()(x) ### U-NET layer upsampling from (112, 112, 198) to (224, 224, 198)

    x = Conv2D(1, kernel_size=1, activation="sigmoid")(x) ### Convolution layer from (224, 224, 198) to (224, 224, 1)
    x = Reshape((IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_HEIGHT))(x) ## Reshaping the output to (224, 224)

    return Model(inputs=model.input, outputs=x)

Call the create_model function¶

  • Given trainable=False as argument, to freeze lower layers for fast training (but low accuracy)
In [59]:
model = create_model(False)

Define dice coefficient function¶

  • Create a function to calculate dice coefficient
In [61]:
def dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred):
    numerator = 2 * tensorflow.reduce_sum(y_true * y_pred)
    denominator = tensorflow.reduce_sum(y_true + y_pred)

    return numerator / (denominator + tensorflow.keras.backend.epsilon())

Define loss function¶

In [62]:
def loss(y_true, y_pred):
    return binary_crossentropy(y_true, y_pred) - tensorflow.keras.backend.log(dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred) + tensorflow.keras.backend.epsilon())

Compile the model¶

  • Complie the model using below parameters
    • loss: use the loss function defined above
    • optimizers: use Adam optimizer
    • metrics: use dice_coefficient function defined above
In [63]:
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
from tensorflow.keras.losses import binary_crossentropy

optimizer = Adam(lr=1e-4, beta_1=0.9, beta_2=0.999, epsilon=None, decay=0.0, amsgrad=False)
model.compile(loss=loss, optimizer=optimizer, metrics=[dice_coefficient])

Define callbacks¶

  • Use ModelCheckpoint
  • Use EarlyStopping
  • Use ReduceLROnPlateau
In [64]:
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint, EarlyStopping, ReduceLROnPlateau

checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("model-{val_loss:.2f}.h5", monitor="val_loss", verbose=1, save_best_only=True, save_weights_only=True)

stop = EarlyStopping(monitor="val_loss", patience=5)

reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor="val_loss", factor=0.2, patience=5, min_lr=1e-6, verbose=1)

Impose the mask on the test image¶

  • In imshow using the alpha parameter and set it to greater than 0.5
In [126]:
### Function to show the test image with corresponding expected and predected mask images. ###
def preview_results(image_index):
  print("Test image_index = ",image_index)   
  test_image = X_test[image_index]

  pred_mask = cv2.resize(1.0*(model.predict(x=np.array([test_image]))[0] > 0.5), (IMAGE_WIDTH,IMAGE_HEIGHT))
  pred_mask_image = copy.deepcopy(test_image)
  pred_mask_image[:,:,0] = pred_mask*test_image[:,:,0]
  pred_mask_image[:,:,1] = pred_mask*test_image[:,:,1]
  pred_mask_image[:,:,2] = pred_mask*test_image[:,:,2]

  expected_mask = cv2.resize(1.0*(y_test[image_index] > 0.5), (IMAGE_WIDTH,IMAGE_HEIGHT))
  expected_mask_image = copy.deepcopy(test_image)
  expected_mask_image[:,:,0] = expected_mask*test_image[:,:,0]
  expected_mask_image[:,:,1] = expected_mask*test_image[:,:,1]
  expected_mask_image[:,:,2] = expected_mask*test_image[:,:,2]

  suppress_spam_logs()
  f, axarr = plt.subplots(1,3, figsize=(20, 6))
  axarr[0].imshow(test_image)
  axarr[0].set_title("Test Image")
  axarr[1].imshow(expected_mask_image)
  axarr[1].set_title("Expected Mask Image")
  axarr[2].imshow(pred_mask_image)
  axarr[2].set_title("Predicted Mask Image")
  plt.show()
  reset_logs()

for i in range(X_test.shape[0]):
    preview_results(i)

Summary¶

  • This project goal is to predict the mask around the faces in a given image
  • The given images are with different sizes and different channels
  • First we have normalized the given images by scaling (224, 224, 3) and preprocessed them to use in mobilenet
  • With transfer learning using mobilenet we have defined a U_Net by adding 6 more upsampling layers to get the output images with (224,224)
  • For the defined model parameters summary is like Total params: 3,230,849 Trainable params: 1,985 and Non-trainable params: 3,228,864
  • We split the data like 400 trainset and 9 testset
  • We have defined the loss function with dice coefficient and callbacks with val_loss monitoring with early stop of 5 patience value and reducelrplateau with min_lr of 1e-6
  • Run the model with hyper parameters of batch size is 1 and the no of epochs are 10 ( I have tried with different batch sizes like 16 and 32 also which are fast but consuming much RAM and the model convergence seems slow compare to batch size 1)
  • The result is with loss: 0.8320 - dice_coefficient: 0.5850 - val_loss: 0.8239 - val_dice_coefficient: 0.5869
  • We have verified the model performance by imposing expected mask and the predected mask on all the test images and listed down this comparison for reference.
